\section{Skew Confluence} \label{sec:skew-confluence}

\skewtodo{This is a sketch of an incomplete proof of skew confluence.}

We now consider a version of \versecalc{} that fully supports recursive substitution,
and lifts the pesky no-recursion precondition on the confluence theorem.
Rather than lifting the side condition $|x| \not\in \freevars{v}$
on rule \rulename{subst}, which avoids using a recursive equation for substitution,
we take another approach that we believe leads to a simpler proof:
we introduce the familiar, conventional fixpoint operator |mu x hnf|, but allow it to be applied only to head values, not to general expressions.
A new unification rule \rulename{u-occurs-wrap} can turn a recursive equation into one that is not recursive
(by packaging up the right-hand side within a fixpoint), after which rule \rulename{subst} may be applied.
A corresponding new rule \rulename{u-unwrap} can expand a fixpoint by applying the conventional rewrite rule
$|mu x hnf| \movesto |subst hnf x (mu x hnf)|$. While this rule allows infinite application,
a sensible evaluation strategy would apply this rule ``only when needed''---when it is on either side of an equation,
or when it is in the function position of an application. If we regard any \versecalc{} data structure as tree,
the fixpoint construct in effect can label any subtree in such a way that any node beneath it can have a ``back pointer'' up to the labeled node
by referring to the bound variable that serves as the label. 

The overall plan is to adapt the proof strategy
of \cref{sec:confluence-sketch} and \cref{sec:confluence} for skew confluence.
To do this we need a new result: if two relations are skew confluent
with respect to the same information content function and commute, then their union is also skew confluent.
(In fact, it is not required that the two relations fully commute: a slightly weaker precondition suffices.)
Using this result, our plan
is to (i) define an appropriate information content function for \versecalc{} expressions;
(ii) prove that all the rewrite rules for \versecalc{} are monotonic in this information content function;
(iii) prove that the Unification rules (modified to permit recursive substitution) together with the Normalization rules are skew confluent;
(iv) prove that this combined set of rules commutes in the necessary way with the rules for Application, Elimination, and Choice (which taken together are already known to be confluent);
and (v) then apply our new result to show that the entire set of rewrite rules is skew confluent.
At this time steps (iii) and (iv) are incomplete, so we emphasize that we do not yet have a complete proof of skew confluence for \versecalc{}.

\subsection{Free Variables}


We use the conventional notation $\freevars{|e|}$ to denote the set of variables that occur free
in the expression |e|. Variables are bound by the constructs |def x e|, |lam x e|, and |mu x hnf|.
\Cref{fig:fvs} contains a formal definition of this function for \versecalc{}.

We use the variation $\freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e|}$ to denote the set of variables that occur free
in the expression |e| in at least one position that is not within the body of a
lambda expression\footnote{
  ``$\freevarsoutsidelambdas{\cdot}$'' abbreviates ``free variables outside lambda''}.
As an example, $\freevarsoutsidelambdas{|def x (tup (x, f, g, lam y (tup (x, g, y, z))))|} = \{ f, g \}$ because:
\begin{itemize}
\item |x| is bound by |defKW|, so it is not free. 
\item |f| is free in a position not within the body of a lambda expression.
\item |g| is free in at least one position not within the body of a lambda expression (it also happens to be free in a second position that is within the body of a lambda expression).
\item |y| is bound by |lambda|, so it is not free. 
\item |z| is free, but appears only in a position that is within the body of a lambda expression.
\end{itemize}
\Cref{fig:fvsol} contains a formal definition of this function.
Unlike $\freevars{e}$, $\freevarsoutsidelambdas{|v|}$ is only ever appplied to a value $|v|$.

\subsection{Substitution}

We use the notation |subst e x v| to denote the expression that results from performing standard capture-avoiding substitution of the value |v| for every occurrence of the variable |x| within the expression |e| (it turns out that, for \versecalc{}, substitution of general expressions for variables is not required, only substitution of values for variables).
\Cref{fig:substitution} contains a formal definition of how this notation applies to the \versecalc{} grammar (compare \cite[\S 2.1.15]{Barendregt}).

\subsection{Modified grammar and rewrite rules}

Let us modify the grammar for \versecalc{} to have one additional kind of value, a~\emph{fixpoint} value |mu x hnf|:
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{lr@@{\;}c@@{\;}l}
      \text{Values} & |v| & ::= & |x|  \vb \hnf \vb |mu x hnf| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
and a modify the set of Unification rewrite rules $\runi$ so that rule \rulename{u-occurs}
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-occurs} & |x=V^[x]| & \movesto & |fail| & \text{if $|V| \ne |hole|$} \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
is replaced by the two rules\footnote{These two rules allow equations to be recursive through lambda expressions and possibly also tuples, but not through tuples only;
  thus equations such as |f = lam y (tup (y, f))| and |x = (tup (1,  lam y (tup (y, x))))| can be processed by rule \rulename{u-occurs-wrap},
  but the equation |x = (tup (1, x))| can be processed only by rule \rulename{u-occurs-fail}.
  An alternate design using the single rule
  \begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-occurs-wrap} & |x=hnf| & \movesto & |x=mu x hnf| & \text{if $|x| \in \freevars{|hnf|}$} \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
plus rule \rulename{u-unwrap} could be used instead to support recursion through tuples only as well as through lambda expressions.}\footnote{
  \rulename{u-occurs-fail} is identical to \rulename{u-occurs} in its effect,
  but it is re-expressed using $\freevarsoutsidelambdas{\cdot}$, which we need anyway for \rulename{u-occurs-wrap}.  Now we can drop the context $V$, which was only
  used in \rulename{u-occurs}.
}
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-occurs-fail} & |x=hnf; e| & \movesto & |fail| & \text{if $|x| \in \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|hnf|}$} \\
  \rulename{u-occurs-wrap} & |x=hnf; e| & \movesto & |x=mu x hnf; e| & \text{if $|x| \in \freevars{|hnf|}$ and $|x| \not\in \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|hnf|}$} \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
Let us also add this rewrite rule:
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-unwrap} & |mu x hnf| & \movesto & |subst hnf x (mu x hnf)| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
As we will see, rule \rulename{u-unwrap} is confluent but not Noetherian.

The resulting grammar is not confluent; in particular, it suffers from the even-odd problem
described in \cref{sec:even-odd} \cite[Example 4.1]{ariola:skew-confluence}.
Therefore we will modify the proof of confluence for $\runi$ to become a proof of \emph{skew confluence} \cite{ariola:skew-confluence},
and then go on to prove that \versecalc{} itself, with this modification, is skew confluent.


