\begin{lemma}\label{lem:critpairs}\cite[Lemma 3.1]{Huet80}
The relation $\go{\rr}$ is locally confluent iff for every critical pair |(e_1, e_2)| of $\rr$, |e_1| and |e_2| can be \emph{joined}---that is, there exists |e_3| such that
 $|e_1| \go{\rr} |e_3|$ and  $|e_2| \go{\rr} |e_3|$.
\end{lemma}


\begin{lemma}[$\rinfo$-Confluent] \label{lem:rinfo-c}
$\rinfo$ is locally confluent and Noetherian; therefore $\rinfo$ is confluent.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  Consider all critical pairs of $\rinfo$:
  \begin{itemize}
\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-l} and \rulename{info-fail-r} produce the critical pair |(Omega, Omega)|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-l} and \rulename{info-choice-omega} produce no critical pairs.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-l} and \rulename{info-choice-assoc} produce the critical pair |(Omega choice e, Omega)|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-r} and \rulename{info-choice-omega} produce the critical pair |(Omega, Omega)|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-r} and \rulename{info-choice-assoc} produce the critical pairs |(Omega, Omega)| and |(Omega choice e, Omega)|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-choice-omega} and \rulename{info-choice-assoc} produce the critical pair |(Omega choice e, Omega)|.

\item  No other pairs of rules produce any critical pairs.
\end{itemize}
The critical pair |(Omega, Omega)| can be trivially joined at |Omega|.
The critical pair |(Omega choice e, Omega)| can be joined at |Omega| in one step by using rule \rulename{info-choice-omega} on |Omega choice e|.

All critical pairs can be joined; therefore by \cref{lem:critpairs} $\rinfo$ is locally confluent.

Let the size of a term of $\vcOmega$ be the number of tokens it contains other than parentheses.
Each of the rewrite rules in \cref{fig:info-rewrite-rules} strictly decreases the number of such tokens.
Because any given term has a finite number $n$ of such tokens, and the number of tokens cannot be less than zero,
for every term every rewriting sequence from that term can have no more than $n$ steps. So $\rinfo$ is bounded and therefore Noetherian.

Because $\rinfo$ is locally confluent and Noetherian, it is confluent by Newman's lemma.
\end{proof}

Because $\rinfo$ is confluent and Noetherian, it follows that $\rinfo$ defines unique normal forms for $\vcOmega$. Therefore we are justified in defining
$\omegavc(e)$ to be the function that takes any term in $\vcOmega$ and returns the term that is its normal form under $\rinfo$.

\begin{definition}
The comparison $e \leqomegavc e'$ is defined to mean $\omegavc(e) \leqomega \omegavc(e')$.
\end{definition}

\skewtodo{Need to prove that $\leqomegavc$ is monotonic with respect to $\leqomega$; this should be routine \cite[Proposition 5.21]{ariola:skew-confluence}.}

\begin{lemma}[\versecalc{} monotonic] \label{lem:vc-monotonic}
Every rewrite rule in \versecalc{} is monotonic with respect to $\leqomegavc$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  For every rewrite rule in $\rapp \cup \runi \cup \rcon \cup \rgc \cup \rspc$,
  the left-hand side is an expression that is mapped to |Omega| by the function $\omegavc$,
  and no matter what expression |e| is the result of applying $\omegavc$ to the right-hand side,
  we have $|Omega| \leqomega |e|$.
 \end{proof}

\subsection{Preliminaries about Skew Confluence}


\begin{comment}
\subsection{Overview of Skew Confluence (VERSION 1)} \label{sec:skew-overview}


If a reduction relation $\rr$ is confluent, then for all |e|, |e_1|, and |e_2|,
if $\rstep{\rr}{|e|}{|e_1|}$ and $\rstep{\rr}{|e|}{|e_2|}$ then there exists |e'| such that
if $\rstep{\rr}{|e_1|}{|e'|}$ and $\rstep{\rr}{|e_2|}{|e'|}$.
This is useful because the $\rr$-normal form (if it exists) of any expression is if $\rr$ is confluent.

But what can we say if $\rr$ is not confluent---for example, what if $\rr$ has the even-odd problem
discussed in \cref{sec:even-odd}? Ariola and Blom introduced a notion of \emph{infinite normal form},
which is a (possibly infinite) set of (possibly \emph{erased}) terms rather than a single term.
We summarize this idea, using our own terminology, as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item Let an \emph{erasure} of a term be a copy in which one or more subterms (possibly the entire term)
  have been replaced with |Omega|, a special term that means ``unknown'' or ``we don't know yet.''
\item We can compare possibly erased terms with the partial order $\leqomega$, which is the transitive,
  reflexive, and compatible closure of the relation in which |Omega| is less than any other term.
  Observe that if |e'| is an erasure of |e| then $|e'| \leqomega |e|$.
\item Define the $\rr$-\emph{information content} $\omegarr(|e|)$ of an expression |e| to be the unique erasure of |e| in which \emph{every} redex
  has been replaced by |Omega|. Any non-|Omega| structure in the result is therefore ``permanent'':
  no further reductions under $\rr$ can alter that structure.
\item For any expression |e|, consider the (possibly infinite) set $A$ of all its $\rr$-reducts, that is, \emph{all} expressions |e'| such that
  $\rstep{\rr}{e}{e'}$, then let $B = \{ \omegarr(|e|) \mid |e| \in A\}$.
  The \emph{infinite $\rr$-normal form} of |e| is a set $C$, the \emph{downward closure} of $B$ under $\leqomega$; that is,
  for every element of $B$, $C$ contains not only that element but also every possible erasure of that element.
\end{itemize}
It is the step of taking a downward closure under $\leqomega$ that makes it possible to prove that infinite normal forms
are unique for certain reduction relations.

But working with these infinite sets directly is tricky. Fortunately, there is a simpler path, because Ariola and Blom also prove
an important theorem: a reduction relation that is \emph{monotonic} (meaning that no rewrite rule ever decreases the information content)
has unique infinite normal forms if and only if the reduction relation is \emph{skew confluent} \cite[Theorem 5.4]{ariola:skew-confluence}---and skew
confluence is much easier to prove, using techniques that do not involve infinite sets, but are fairly similar to proofs of ordinary confluence
that use commutative diagrams and case analysis.

Here, then, is the idea behind skew confluence: for all |e|, |e_1|, and |e_2|,
if $\rstep{\rr}{|e|}{|e_1|}$ and $\rstep{\rr}{|e|}{|e_2|}$, then there may not be any |e'| such that
if $\rstep{\rr}{|e_1|}{|e'|}$ and $\rstep{\rr}{|e_2|}{|e'|}$. Instead, you can choose either of |e_1| and |e_2| (let's say |e_2|),
and then there does exists some |e'| such that $\rstep{\rr}{|e_1|}{|e'|}$ and |e'| has at least as much information content as |e_2|,
that is, $\omegarr(|e_2|) \leqomega \omegarr(|e'|)$. This works both ways, by symmetry, because the choice of |e_1| or |e_2| is arbitrary.

In the case of the even-odd problem discussed in \cref{sec:even-odd}, further reductions on the two expressions
|def y (y == lam z (tup (1, y); tup (1,y))| and |def x (x = tup (1, lam z x)); x| might produce longer expressions such as
|def y (y == lam z (tup (1, y)); tup (1, lam z (tup (1, lam z (tup (1, y))))))|
and |def x (x = tup (1, lam z x); tup (1, lam z (tup (1, lam z (tup (1, lam z x))))))|.
One can see that each of these expressions
will produce a value of the form |tup (1, lam z (tup (1, lam z (tup (1, ctrdots))))))|. Confluence cannot be achieved,
because no matter how many times one substitutes for |y| in the first expression or for |x| in the second expression,
the first expression will always have one more occurrence of ``|1|'' than ``|lamhdr z|'' but the second expression
will always have the same number of occurrences of ``|1|'' than ``|lamhdr z|''; on the other hand, no matter
how long one expression becomes through substitution, the other one can be made even longer,
so as to have at least as much information content (and in fact more, in this example). The theory of skew confluence makes this idea precise.

Another important fact is that if a reduction relation is confluent and monotonic, then it is skew confluent
\cite[Corollary 5.5]{ariola:skew-confluence}. In \cref{sec:skew-confluence} we prove a new result: if two relations are skew confluent
with respect to the same information content function and commute, then their union is also skew confluent.
(In fact, it is not required that the two relations fully commute; a slightly weaker precondition suffices.)
This provides a detailed strategy for reusing parts of the proof of confluence for \versecalc{} sketched in \cref{sec:confluence-sketch}
and detailed in \cref{sec:confluence}: our plan is to (i) define an appropriate information content function for \versecalc{} expressions;
(ii) prove that all the rewrite rules for \versecalc{} are monotonic in this information content function;
(iii) prove that the Unification rules (modified to permit recursive substitution) together with the Normalization rules are skew confluent;
(iv) prove that this combined set of rules commutes in the necessary way with the rules for Application, Elimination, and Choice (which taken together are already known to be confluent);
and (v) then apply our new result to show that the entire set of rewrite rules is skew confluent.
At this time steps (iii) and (iv) are incomplete, so we emphasize that \emph{we do not yet have a complete proof of skew confluence for \versecalc{}}.
